	<annotation>
		<!-- Marginalia -->
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="head" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Maxim&egrave; sapit, qui prouidet maxim&egrave;, vt &agrave; Seipso dependeat:
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="&agrave; Seipso dependeat"/>
				</position>
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						quantu[m] facere
						potest vllo modo.
						Summa summaru[m] Epicteti, Seneca[e], Antonini.
						Quomod&ograve; Crates; nihilo egere philosophum.
						Stoici; Omnia esse Sapientum. 
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Epictetus"/>
					<person name="Seneca"/>
					<person name="Marcus Aurelius"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<language ident="EL">
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						ὅτι
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						μόνος ὁ σοφὸς πλούσιος.
						ὅτι ἀυταρκὴς ἡ ἀρετὴ πρὸς ἐυδαιμονϊαν.
					</marginalia_text>
					<X-ref person="Cicero" book_title="Paradoxa Stoicorum" language="EL" text="μόνος ὁ σοφὸς πλούσιος"/>
					<X-ref person="Cicero" book_title="Paradoxa Stoicorum" language="EL" text="ὅτι ἀυταρκὴς ἡ ἀρετὴ πρὸς ἐυδαιμονϊαν"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				He who takes care the most that he depend only on himself is he who knows the most.
				And he can do as much as possible in any way.
				The sum of sums of Epictetus, of Seneca, of Marus Aurelius.
				Crates in the same manner -- that the philosopher needs nothing. <!-- CG: I can't figure these next two lines out. They might refer to Lipsius or someone else discussing Seneca, Stoicism, etc. Which would explain the weird grammar, i.e. philosophum and sapientum in the accusative. --> <!--JG: Yeah, the grammar is weird indeed. Can't figure this one out either, we should ask a specialist-->
				Of the Stoic: that the wise man is all things.
				"That only the wise man is rich."	<!-- CG: The two Greek phrases come from Cicero's Paradoxa Stoicorum -->
				"That virtue is self-sufficient for happiness."			
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Omnes Magistros superat profundus discipulus.
						Puer est, qui nondum didicit viuere.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The profound disciple surpasses all magistrates.
				He who has not yet learned to live is a child.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Sera nimis sophia est crastina; disce hodi&egrave;.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Tomorrow's wisdom is too late; learn today.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="EL">
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						ὅτι σοφὸι ἐλεύθεροι, καὶ ὁι μωρὸι δοῦλοι.
					</marginalia_text>
					<X-ref person="Cicero" book_title="Paradoxa Stoicorum" language="EL" text="ὅτι σοφὸι ἐλεύθεροι, καὶ ὁι μωρὸι δοῦλοι"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				"That all wise men are free, and all fools are slaves."
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						Crastinia sera nimis copia: cresce hodi&egrave;.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Tomorrow's bounty is too late; grow today. 
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						Eutuchus,
						summus hodiernista. Euemarus, ephermus.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Eutuchus"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Eutuchus, the highest modernist. <!--JG: Part of translation is missing?-->
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
